\begin_layout Subsection
How to cluster users in social media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Model
\series default
: Normally use two algorithms to do clustering: K-means & Gaussian Mixture
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
K-means is to assign a hard label
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Gaussian Mixture is to assign a soft label, which give you a a probability
 of being A or B
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Multiple Tags
\series default
: But the problem is, those models will give you mutually exclusive labels
 : 
\series bold
IN REALITY
\series default
 one user may have 
\series bold
multiple tags
\series default
 / labels at the same.
 One user may love music and computer science at the same time
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
So there is no way to do clustering at just one time
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You need to first choose music related featuresm, do clustering on whether
 a user likes music or not.
 Then run another clustering to decide for the computer science label.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That means, for each time, you just model one label.
 But you run the label multiple times to get all the labels you want.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Hierarchy
\series default
: Also even within the music label, there are further sublabels --- rock,
 pop, rap etc.
 So you have to run clustering in a hierarchical way.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I means first decide all the pepople who like music, then within those people,
 clustering into different groups
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Features used to cluster in social media
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Facebook: Two dimentions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
based on their interests / Base on what they write on their wall: You can
 extract key words / topics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
also interest of the people are following / What those followees write on
 their wall.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Twitter:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Based on what they tweet, y
\series default
ou can use 
\series bold
extract certain key toptics, key words.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Based on who they follow
\series default
: It's hard to directly do clustering on common users.
 But it is relatively easy to cluster those celebrities, they are most likely
 just has oen label --- either movie star, musician, or comupter scientist.
 So their labels are more 
\series bold
pure 
\series default
that common users.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Then we go back to the common users, to see what types of celebrities they
 follow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Or we can even bring the number of likes or retweets for each celebrities,
 using this as a weight to mearue how strong / close this following relation
 is.
 So the following relation is no longer 0 or 1 anymore, it may be 0, 1,
 2, continous integers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Data can be constructed like this: It is a matrix with rows as users, columns
 as celebrities.
 value equal to 1 if a user follow a celebrity, equal to 0 if not.
 OR the value is the total ``
\end_layout

\end_deeper
