Those logged-in users explicitly express their interests, what they care
 about, if they're a Red Sox fan, if they're a Jets fan, if they're Republican
 or Democrat, based on who they're following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Moments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The real question is what value casual, lapsed, and non-users of Twitter
 will find in Moments — and that’s much harder to answer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Their bias is toward tweets from the source: people who are on the scene,
 or are directly involved in the news story.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we try to do is just immerse you in the content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If it sounds like Twitter is now running a media company inside a technology
 company, that’s because it is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One aspect of Moments I didn’t see coming: not every story captures a real-time
 event.
 The company is also packaging together evergreen stories ("Catch a wave,"
 a collection of surfing pictures and videos) and offering them up to browse.
 It's building moments to tell stories that take place over weeks or months
 — a rookie's first month in the National Hockey League, for example, or
 the story of the Los Angeles Dodgers' season.
\end_layout

