\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
50% of time is to develop and maintain loss forecasting models for credit
 card and Personal loans.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
50% of time is to sell our models to Internal customers (marketing / finance).
 That turns out an equally interesting part as building the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our customers are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Largest customer is Marketing: when they need to design some new product,
 or new campaign, they have to come to us to let us run the product through
 our forecasting, to see whether they can make money.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
They have strong incentive to question our model accuracy, but only when
 our forecasting loss is too high and kills their product.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Treasury: report them DEFAST.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finance: loss reserve calculation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the model developing part, I recently redeveloped the whole personal
 consolidation loans.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The structure of the model is flexible enough to be adapted to Mortgage
 and auto-loan.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It can take care both loss and revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Normally a loss forecasting model can only forecast loss and has nothing
 to do with revenue, which restrains the usage of the model.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Traditional model can only start from the very beginning of the loan, this
 model can start from any mob.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also this is the account level model, so you can group whatever way you
 want.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model: One Single Model for Multi-Purposes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why one model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So you see we have multiple customers: marketing, Treasury and Finance.
 So we have to build the forecasting model that is 
\series bold
Generic and Flexible enough
\series default
 that can serve those customers' need at the same time.
 We don't want to build separate models just to serve separate customers
 and different proposes, because essentially they have the same purposes:
 measure the risk of a product under different scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also, Revenue and Loss shall naturally connected and modeled within one
 framework.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thy practice to biuld a model to forecast revenue and then biuld a model
 to forecast loss separately is flawed and redudent.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
So what we are trying to do now, is to build one single loss forecasting
 model for a product, and that model has enough 
\series bold
flexibility and scalability
\series default
 that can extent itself to model the loss at Campaign level, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
offer level, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
then all the way up to the whole portfolio level, which can be used for
 stress testing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise: have multiple models for that product: we have one model to decide
 the potential loss of a campaign, we have another model for collection,
 then we have another model for regulators, like stress testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AND to maintain those models turns out a huge 
\series bold
burden
\series default
 to a middle-size bank like us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Behavior: Team work Experience: work with marketing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example to work with marketing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our bank we have a monthly meeting to decide to whether mail a campaign,
 and I need to provide a loss forecasting for this campaign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If my loss forecasting is too high, and their campaign can not pass the
 Profit hurdle and so they cannot mail the campaign, so often they first
 come to us to argue the forecasting is way to high
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Be 
\series bold
Patient
\series default
, because they don't know your model at all.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
consistent
\series default
 : We also try our best to keep our loss forecasting 
\series bold
consistent
\series default
, so they can have a clear expectation of what offer will pass the profit
 hurdle, what will not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
So everytime before we run the forecasting, we have to talk to them and
 really understand what they 
\series bold
expect.
 
\series default
We don't want to give them a surprise.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Be Proactive:
\series default
 Whenever we made saw some differences in forecasting, I don't wait them
 to come to me, I try to be active to, to talk to them first.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Go further: make the model accessible to everyone.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This is a huge change of our role: originally we are so obsessed with the
 modelling and just though out the output to our business partners, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now we are trying to make the model as a 
\series bold
product
\series default
, 
\series bold
a product that is easy to be used by everyone
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
So in this way, we build a very good working relationship.
 We still have tensions, because Credit Risk and Marketing are naturally
 having opposite interest: we want to control and they want to expand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
But by being more active, more consistent, and communicating more, we worked
 really well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Business: Serve Customer of Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Originally, our model is coded in R, and every time Marketing sends us the
 campaign they want to launch, we plug the characteristics of the campaign
 into our model and give the output back to marketing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is, only we know how to play the model,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So to the marketing people, our model is a 
\series bold
black box
\series default
, or our whole risk department is a black box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But they user and consumer of the model, don't even have access to the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The efficacy /ˈefəkəsē/ of your model does not only depend on the model
 itself, but on how the model users use the result your model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
So what I did there, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
instead of using the model for each campaign at one time and using the model
 only we know the campaign.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I summarized all the historical campaigns and find all possible combination,
 for example, different combinations of APR, fees, channels etc.
 In total there are hundreds of possible campaigns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Output the model's result into a pivot table in excel, with some dynamic
 graphs, where you can click the VBA button so that they can choose mix
 of offers, channels and segmentation and automatically see the loss curve
 and profit curve.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
So after this become a user tool, when marking design their offer, they
 will see the profitability and loss vividly 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Business: Communicating with Marketing in loss curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Background:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
There is a natural conflict between any marketing person and a risk person.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They have strong interests to question the accuracy of our loss curves,
 but only when it is so high to let their campaign fail in P&L evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They are non- technical people; they have no idea in 
\series bold
overfitting
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EXAMPLE: sometimes you have to convince them one good performance campaign
 cannot represent anything, what we want to see is a continues good performance
 for all similar campaigns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You have to really show a large amount of historical data and show them
 graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Be active: talk to them before they talk to you.
 To show you are a 
\series bold
\emph on
responsible and responsive
\emph default
 person.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Be consistent on your result 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Be Patient 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model: UCL forecasting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
complications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ultimate goal is to build a model that can forecast loss curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several features for this model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For each time, we just forecast one period ahead, then we plug in the predicted
 result into the model again to forecast one period further.
 First from to T to T+1, then based on predictions on T+1, we predict T+2.
 So we keep doing this kind of thing recursively till T+N.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a reason we design our model in this way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is hard to find a closed form equation to generate a curve at once.
 When you are talking a loss curve, that is the loss dollar rate for 60
 months or even 72 months.
 It is hard to use a single equation to describe the shape of the curve,
 how high the peak is, when is the peak, what happens after the peak (should
 it stay high, or sharply decrease or slowly decrease).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Also accounts with different FICO or in different loan terms shall naturally
 have different shapes of the curve.
 When I mean different shapes I mean you cannot just adjust the curve proportion
ally to fit different risk groups.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Another feature of this model is, this model predicts every aspect of an
 account behaviors, including charge-off, delinquent, early payment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The way we are doing this is, we create multiple equations and each equation
 just described one single kind of behavior.
 When we use them, we link them together.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For example, the first LOGIT equation to predict charge-off, then we simulate
 accounts through this equation,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if the account is not predicted to be charged off, 
\series bold
then given that updated information
\series default
, we plug it in the second equation to predict delinquency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then third one is, 
\series bold
given they are not delinquent,
\series default
 whether they will do early pay, the fourth one is given they will do early
 pay, how much they will pay.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
So each time, we just focus on one kind of behavior, then predict it, then
 utilize the updated information to predict another kind of behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The dollar loss rate is determined by the probability of charge off, but
 also determined by the charge off amount
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
So to predict PD is not enough, so you to predict balance, and to predict
 balance, you have to predict the payment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
PD and EAD are not separated things.
 They are interactive with each other.
 They shall be incorporated in the one forecasting system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
If you really want to forecast dollar loss rate correctly, you have to forecast
 things beyond loss correctly.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
So in this way, we decompose the complexity of different customer behaviors
 each single component, and by linking these different equations, we can
 forecast the PD and EAD together, simultaneously.
\end_layout

